        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>805 Lexington Ave.<lb/>
                New York May 18<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1879<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. and dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Mr Phillips was<lb/> Reader in our synagogue for<lb/> about ten years.  He was quite<lb/> satsifactory as a Reader&#44;<lb/> except that he did not attempt<lb/> to read the Torah.  His indolence<lb/> was the only fault that I could<lb/> instance as incurable.  We should<lb/> have retained him but for the<lb/> consideration of economy.  The<lb/> appropriation for Reader is<lb/> now about &#36;1000&#44; whilst Mr.<lb/> Phillips received &#36;2250.<lb/></p>
            <p>He has lived a blameless<lb/> life&#8212;is&#44; however&#44; an overgrown<lb/> boy&#44; so simple hearted and<lb/> unsophisticated.  For the ten<lb/> years &#40;or more&#41; that he was<lb/> associated with my dear<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>father&#44; he was true and faithful<lb/> in synagogue work&#59; and&#44; had he<lb/> been more the man of the world&#44;<lb/> would have saved something out of<lb/> his excellent income and been<lb/> able to remain at a reduced<lb/> salary until times improved&#44; but<lb/> he had been incapable of managing<lb/> his finances&#44; and there was a<lb/> collection made whose proceeds he<lb/> invested in a cigar store&#8212;and lost.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have spoken of the material<lb/> side&#44; because that is the aspect<lb/> in which I must criticize.  He has<lb/> otherwise&#44; every qualification for<lb/> the post of Reader &#40;and&#44; perhaps&#44;<lb/> you will quietly smile at my<lb/> recognition of the business quali<lb/>fication as essential&#8212;but then I<lb/> find that the two most successful<lb/> Readers in our city &#40;Rubin and<lb/> Sternberger&#8212;are <hi rend="underline">excellent</hi> business<lb/> men&#41;.<lb/></p>
            <p>With Mr Phillips&#44; everything depends<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>on the President of the Congn.  If<lb/> Mr. Brunswick will act as<lb/> mentor&#44; Mr Phillips will prove<lb/> a faithful&#44; reliable and useful<lb/> Hazan and will be kindly<lb/> regarded by the whole congregation.<lb/>  As for his style of reading&#44;<lb/> I have never had occasion to<lb/> find fault&#8212;he sang feelingly<lb/> and correctly with or without a<lb/> choir and gave the old melodies with spirit<lb/> and appreciated the newer<lb/> synagogue music.  He is a<lb/> good Hebrew teacher&#44; provided<lb/> he is aided in maintaining<lb/> discipline.<lb/></p>
            <p>You have heard of the deep<lb/> affliction that has befallen us<lb/> in the death of my brother&#39;s wife<lb/> Just as we were closing the<lb/> year of mourning for our lamented<lb/> father&#44; came this sorrow&#44; and<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>simultaneously we had the news<lb/> of our honored uncle&#39;s death.<lb/>  We are&#44; indeed&#44; taught the<lb/> severe lesson of resignation.<lb/></p>
            <p>Sincerely Yours&#44;<lb/>
                M. S. Isaacs.<lb/></p>
        </body>
